📘 Components of Selenium
1. Selenium is a web automation tool used to control browsers using programming languages like Python 
    Java , C# etc..
2. It works on:
    -> All major browsers
    -> All major OS
    -> Multiple programming languages
3. Selenium has 4 main components:
    -> Selenium IDE
    -> Selenium RC
    -> Selenium WebDriver
    -> Selenium Grid

1️⃣ Selenium IDE
    What is it?
    -----------
    Selenium IDE is a browser extension used for recording and playing back tests.

    Mainly used for
    ---------------
    1. Beginners
    2. Quick test execution
    3. Learning automation

    features
    --------
    1. Record and Playback user actions
    2. Uses Selenese language
    3. Can export tests to java , Python , C# , Ruby
    4. Works only with Chrome and FireFox
    5. Basic debugging(pause , step , inspect)

👉 Easy to use but not suitable for complex automation.

2️⃣ Selenium RC (Remote Control)
    What is it?
    -----------
    Selenium RC is an older selenium tool used before WebDriver.

    How it worked?
    --------------
    1. Required a server
    2. Server acted as middlemen between test code and browser

    Disadvantages
    -------------
    1. Slower performance
    2. Complicated setup
    3. Not good for modern applications
👉 Now replaced by WebDriver.

3️⃣ Selenium WebDriver
    What is it?
    -----------
    Selenium WebDriver is the main and most important component of selenium.

    Why is it better than RC?
    -------------------------
    1. Directly communicates with browser
    2. No server needed
    3. Faster execution
    4. Better support for modern websites (HTML5 , CSS# , JavaScript)

    Features
    --------
    1. Control browser actions
    2. Handles alerts and windows
    3. Navigate pages
    4. Perform parallel execution
    5. Rick APIs
👉 Most used Selenium tool in real-time projects.

4️⃣ Selenium Grid
    What is it?
    -----------
    Selenium Grid allows running tests on multiple machines and browsers at the same time.

    How it works?
    -------------
    1. One machine acts as Hub
    2. Other machines atcs as Nodes
    3. Tests are sent to Hub -> executed on Nodes

    Benefits
    --------
    1. Parallel Testing
    2. Cross-browser testing
    3. Test on different OS
    4. Faster execution







